Non-invasive continuous cardiac output (CCO) monitors have become popular in operating rooms and intensive care units (ICUs). However, the inaccuracy of arterial waveform analysis for measuring CCO associated with changes in systemic vascular resistance (SVR) has been well documented [1, 2]. Sugo et al. [3] developed a new non-invasive CCO monitoring system called estimated continuous cardiac output (esCCO). In the esCCO system, CCO is derived by means of a conventional electrocardiogram (ECG) monitor, peripheral pulse oximetry (SpO2) system, and arterial pulse pressure. The esCCO system uses pulse wave transit time (PWTT) in place of arterial waveform analysis. PWTT is the sum of the pre-ejection period (PEP) and the time taken for pulse wave to travel from the ascending aorta to the SpO2 probe site (Fig. 1). PWTT is calculated from the interval between the R wave peak of the ECG and the rise point of peripheral SpO2 pulse wave when the ECG and SpO2 are recorded simultaneously. Stroke volume (SV) is derived as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
